svg.text: Hi Alessia, can we talk about the difference
between a zoo and a circus?
Yes, happy to chat! I’m not really
an expert though.
That’s fine! I just wanted to hear your
thoughts. So, what’s the first thing that
comes to your mind when you think of a
zoo?
Um… animals in cages, I guess?
Like lions, monkeys, that sort of
thing. It’s where people go to see
animals.
Right, and what about a circus?
That’s more like… clowns and
acrobats, and sometimes animals
doing tricks. Though I don’t think
I’ve seen one with animals since I
was a kid.
Yeah, that makes sense. The main difference
is that zoos are usually focused on taking
care of animals, showing how they live, and
sometimes helping endangered species.
Circuses, especially in the past, used ani
mals more for entertainment, making
them do tricks for a prize.
Oh, I never really thought
about that. I guess the ani
mals in circuses did not live a
happy life.
Exactly. A lot of them were kept in small
cages and traveled constantly. That’s
really stressful for wild animals. That’s
why many places have banned animal
acts in circuses now.
That’s a good thing. Are zoos
perfect then?
Not always. Some zoos don’t have great
conditions either. But the better ones try
to create natural habitats and educate
people about the animals. The differen
ce is mostly in how the animals get trea
ted.
Got it. What about the
Dolfinarium?
The Dolfinarium is interesting because it’s not
quite a zoo, but also not a traditional circus.
They focus on sea animals, mainly dolphins,
and they do shows with them.
Right, like when the dolphins jump
and spin in the air on command.
Yeah, and that’s where the debate starts. Some
people say those shows are entertaining and
educational, but others feel like it’s too close
to circus-style performances and not respect
ful of the animals' natural behavior.
Hmm. I guess if the dolphins are
doing tricks just for the audience, it
kind of feels more like a circus.
Exactly. The question is whether those shows
actually help people learn, or if it’s just enter
tainment with animals doing unnatural things.
That’s a good way to put it. And that's why
it’s such a debated topic. Some people
think places like the Dolfinarium should
change and focus more on conservation
and less on shows.
Yeah, especially now that people
are more aware of animal rights
Yes, an issue raised by activists of Bite Back
and Active for Justice is the ongoing use of
dolphins and sea lions in performances.
They say that trainers are still allowed to
surf on the dolphins' noses and make sea
lions wave their flippers at the audience.
These actions violate agreements made
with the government regarding the use of
animals for entertainment.
Using the animals in this way
would make the park more like a
circus than a zoo then.
Definitely. And using animals for entertai

Dolfinarium is considered a zoo by the
government. They hide behind the fact that
they do school trips and are here to educa
te children on the dolphins.
But if they're a zoo they should
actually stop the shows then
Yes, in theory they should. And let's not

animals. They live in small tanks only 5
meters deep.

how do they not hurt
